*=F0=9F=A7=AA What Did the Study Do?*

This paper replicated and extended a landmark 2015 study by looking at
brain scans and lifestyle data from thousands of American children (ages
9=E2=80=9310) participating in the NIH-funded ABCD Study. It used advanced =
math to
find patterns connecting brain activity with personal traits like academic
performance, risk-taking, family income, and mental health symptoms.


The researchers confirmed a *=E2=80=9Cpositive=E2=80=93negative axis=E2=80=
=9D* of brain function:


   -

   Kids who scored higher on this axis tended to do better in school, had
   fewer behavioral issues, and came from more stable households.
   -

   Kids who scored lower showed more signs of difficulties like ADHD
   symptoms, rule-breaking, and emotional challenges.

